<section id="what-is">
      <h2>What Are Chinese Martial Arts?</h2>
      <p>Chinese martial arts (<span class="chinese-char">武術</span>, Wǔshù, literally "martial techniques"), known globally as <em>kung fu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">功夫</span>, gōngfu, actually meaning "skill achieved through effort"), encompass hundreds of fighting styles developed across China over millennia. They are far more than combat systems &mdash; at their deepest level, they are physical expressions of Chinese philosophy, medicine, and cosmology.</p>
      <p>The character <span class="chinese-char">武</span> (wǔ, martial) is composed of <span class="chinese-char">止</span> (to stop) and <span class="chinese-char">戈</span> (a weapon), conveying the paradox at the heart of Chinese martial philosophy: the highest martial achievement is the ability to <em>stop conflict</em>, not to perpetuate it.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="history">
      <h2>Historical Development</h2>
      <p>Chinese martial arts evolved through several distinct phases:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ancient Period (pre-Qin)</strong> &mdash; Military combat techniques (<span class="chinese-char">技擊</span>) developed for battlefield use. The <em>Zhuangzi</em> records sword fighting as an art form by the 4th century BCE. Wrestling (<span class="chinese-char">角力</span>) was practised from the Zhou Dynasty.</li>
        <li><strong>Shaolin Emergence (5th-6th century CE)</strong> &mdash; Tradition credits the Indian monk Bodhidharma (<span class="chinese-char">達摩</span>) with introducing exercises at Shaolin Temple that evolved into martial forms. While historically debated, the Shaolin Temple became China's most famous martial arts centre by the Tang Dynasty, when its warrior monks aided Li Shimin in founding the dynasty.</li>
        <li><strong>Song-Ming Flourishing</strong> &mdash; Martial arts diversified into numerous regional styles. General Yue Fei (<span class="chinese-char">岳飛</span>) is legendarily credited with creating Xingyiquan and Eagle Claw styles. The Ming Dynasty general Qi Jiguang documented 32 forms of boxing in his military treatise.</li>
        <li><strong>Ming-Qing Internal Arts</strong> &mdash; Taijiquan, Baguazhang, and Xingyiquan emerged as distinct internal traditions, emphasising qi cultivation and Daoist philosophy alongside martial application.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="external">
      <h2>External Styles (<span class="chinese-char">外家</span>)</h2>
      <p>External styles, broadly associated with the <strong>Shaolin tradition</strong>, emphasise physical conditioning, speed, explosive power, and clearly defined techniques. They are characterised by dynamic movements, acrobatic kicks, and progressive hardening of the body.</p>
      <p>Major external styles include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Shaolin Quan (<span class="chinese-char">少林拳</span>)</strong> &mdash; The archetypal external style, encompassing dozens of sub-styles with animal imitation forms (Tiger, Crane, Dragon, Snake, Leopard)</li>
        <li><strong>Hung Gar (<span class="chinese-char">洪家</span>)</strong> &mdash; A southern style known for strong stances, tiger and crane techniques, and the Iron Wire form</li>
        <li><strong>Wing Chun (<span class="chinese-char">詠春</span>)</strong> &mdash; A compact southern style emphasising centreline theory, economy of motion, and close-range combat</li>
        <li><strong>Choy Li Fut (<span class="chinese-char">蔡李佛</span>)</strong> &mdash; Combines northern long-range and southern short-range techniques, known for sweeping circular strikes</li>
        <li><strong>Northern Praying Mantis (<span class="chinese-char">螳螂拳</span>)</strong> &mdash; Created by Wang Lang after observing a mantis defeating a cicada, combining mantis-like hooking and trapping with monkey footwork</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="internal">
      <h2>Internal Styles (<span class="chinese-char">內家</span>)</h2>
      <p>The three major internal arts &mdash; often associated with the <strong>Wudang Mountain</strong> tradition and Daoist philosophy &mdash; prioritise the development of internal energy (<em>neigong</em>, <span class="chinese-char">內功</span>), soft power, and sensitivity:</p>
      <p><strong>Taijiquan (<span class="chinese-char">太極拳</span>)</strong> &mdash; "Supreme Ultimate Fist." Based on the taiji (yin-yang) principle of yielding to overcome force. Practised through slow, continuous forms that cultivate qi and develop <em>ting jin</em> (listening energy). Five major family lineages exist: Chen, Yang, Wu (Hao), Wu, and Sun. Chen style retains the most overt martial content; Yang style is the most widely practised globally.</p>
      <p><strong>Xingyiquan (<span class="chinese-char">形意拳</span>)</strong> &mdash; "Form-Intention Fist." The most directly combative of the internal arts, built on the <a href="/wuxing/">five elements</a>. Its five core techniques map to Metal (splitting), Water (drilling), Wood (crushing), Fire (pounding), and Earth (crossing). Advancing in straight lines, it emphasises explosive forward power generated from internal mechanics.</p>
      <p><strong>Baguazhang (<span class="chinese-char">八卦掌</span>)</strong> &mdash; "Eight Trigram Palm." Based on the <a href="/yijing/">Yi Jing's</a> eight trigrams. Practitioners walk in circles, constantly changing direction and palm techniques. The circular movement reflects the cosmological principle of continuous change and the evasive strategy of flanking opponents.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="five-elements">
      <h2>The Five Elements in Combat</h2>
      <p>Xingyiquan provides the most explicit martial application of <a href="/wuxing/">Wu Xing theory</a>. The five fist techniques follow the generating and overcoming cycles:</p>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Element</th><th>Fist</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Quality</th><th>Overcomes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Metal</td><td>Pi Quan (Splitting)</td><td>劈拳</td><td>Axe-like downward force</td><td>Wood</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Water</td><td>Zuan Quan (Drilling)</td><td>鑽拳</td><td>Rising, penetrating spiral</td><td>Fire</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Wood</td><td>Beng Quan (Crushing)</td><td>崩拳</td><td>Straight, arrow-like strike</td><td>Earth</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fire</td><td>Pao Quan (Pounding)</td><td>炮拳</td><td>Explosive, expanding force</td><td>Metal</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Earth</td><td>Heng Quan (Crossing)</td><td>橫拳</td><td>Lateral, stabilising power</td><td>Water</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>In combat application, recognising an opponent's "element" &mdash; the quality of their energy and movement &mdash; allows the practitioner to spontaneously apply the overcoming technique. This is Wu Xing theory made kinetic.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="animal-styles">
      <h2>Zodiac Animals in Martial Arts</h2>
      <p>Many <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac animals</a> lend their characteristics to distinct martial styles:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dragon (<span class="chinese-char">龍</span>)</strong> &mdash; Cultivating spirit (<em>shen</em>), training the body to move with undulating, serpentine power. Dragon forms emphasise whole-body connection.</li>
        <li><strong>Tiger (<span class="chinese-char">虎</span>)</strong> &mdash; Strengthening bones, developing ferocious power. Tiger techniques feature claw strikes, pouncing, and tearing movements.</li>
        <li><strong>Snake (<span class="chinese-char">蛇</span>)</strong> &mdash; Training internal qi, soft and flowing movement with sudden, precise strikes to vital points.</li>
        <li><strong>Horse (<span class="chinese-char">馬</span>)</strong> &mdash; The <em>ma bu</em> (horse stance) is the foundational posture across virtually all styles. Horse imagery appears in powerful kicking techniques.</li>
        <li><strong>Monkey (<span class="chinese-char">猴</span>)</strong> &mdash; Hou Quan (Monkey Fist) mimics the primate's agility, deceptive movement, and ground techniques.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="medicine">
      <h2>Martial Arts and Chinese Medicine</h2>
      <p>Traditionally, martial artists and physicians were one and the same. The ability to injure required knowledge of the body's vulnerable points &mdash; the same <a href="/tcm/">meridian system</a> that acupuncturists use for healing. <strong>Dit da</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">跌打</span>) medicine &mdash; trauma and injury treatment using herbal liniments, bone-setting, and acupoint therapy &mdash; was an essential component of every martial school's curriculum.</p>
      <p>Qigong (<span class="chinese-char">氣功</span>) and <em>neigong</em> (<span class="chinese-char">內功</span>) exercises serve dual purposes: building internal power for martial application and cultivating health and longevity. The famous <strong>Eight Pieces of Brocade</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">八段錦</span>) and <strong>Five Animal Frolics</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">五禽戲</span>) are health-oriented exercise sets attributed to martial and medical traditions respectively.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="wuxia">
      <h2>Wuxia — The Knight-Errant Tradition (<span class="chinese-char">武俠</span>, <span class="pinyin">Wǔxiá</span>)</h2>
      <p>The concept of <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> (<span class="pinyin">xiá</span>, "knight-errant" or "hero of the martial world") is one of the most enduring ideals in Chinese culture. The <span class="chinese-char">武俠</span> tradition — martial heroes who use their skills to uphold justice, protect the weak, and defy corrupt authority — has roots far deeper than the modern novels and films that popularised it globally.</p>

      <h3>Pre-Qing Literary Sources</h3>
      <div class="source-box">
        <p>The earliest literary treatment of the <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> appears in <strong>Sima Qian's</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">司馬遷</span>) <em>Shiji</em> (<span class="chinese-char">史記</span>, "Records of the Grand Historian," c. 94 BCE). His chapters <em>Cike Liezhuan</em> (<span class="chinese-char">刺客列傳</span>, "Biographies of Assassins") and <em>Youxia Liezhuan</em> (<span class="chinese-char">游俠列傳</span>, "Biographies of Wandering Knights") document historical figures who embodied the <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> code: men who valued loyalty and righteousness above their own lives.</p>
        <cite>— Sima Qian, <em>《史記》</em>, Western Han Dynasty (c. 94 BCE)</cite>
      </div>
      <p>Key stages in the wuxia literary tradition:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Han Dynasty</strong> — Sima Qian established the <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> as a literary archetype. The assassin Jing Ke (<span class="chinese-char">荊軻</span>), who attempted to kill the First Emperor of Qin, became the prototypical <span class="chinese-char">刺客</span>.</li>
        <li><strong>Tang Dynasty</strong> — The <em>chuanqi</em> (<span class="chinese-char">傳奇</span>, "tales of the marvellous") genre produced the first true martial arts fiction. Stories like <em>Kunlun Nu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">崑崙奴</span>, "The Kunlun Slave") and <em>Nie Yinniang</em> (<span class="chinese-char">聶隱娘</span>) featured supernatural swordsmanship and heroic assassins. Du Guangting's (<span class="chinese-char">杜光庭</span>) <em>Qiu Ranke Zhuan</em> (<span class="chinese-char">虬髯客傳</span>) defined the romantic <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> archetype.</li>
        <li><strong>Song–Yuan period</strong> — Vernacular storytelling (<span class="chinese-char">話本</span>, <span class="pinyin">huàběn</span>) brought wuxia tales to mass audiences in urban teahouses. The <em>Water Margin</em> (<span class="chinese-char">水滸傳</span>, <span class="pinyin">Shuǐhǔ Zhuàn</span>), attributed to Shi Nai'an (<span class="chinese-char">施耐庵</span>), compiled Song–Yuan tales of 108 outlaws into what became one of China's Four Great Classical Novels — the defining wuxia text of pre-modern Chinese literature.</li>
        <li><strong>Ming Dynasty</strong> — The genre matured with novels combining martial arts, political intrigue, and Confucian-Buddhist-Taoist philosophy. Judge Bao (<span class="chinese-char">包公</span>) stories blended detective fiction with martial arts themes.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Code of <span class="chinese-char">俠</span></h3>
      <p>The wuxia ethic is built on core principles that predate any formal codification:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">義</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">yì</span>, righteousness) — Doing what is right regardless of personal cost</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">信</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">xìn</span>, trustworthiness) — Keeping one's word absolutely</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">忠</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">zhōng</span>, loyalty) — Unwavering commitment to those who deserve it</li>
        <li><strong><span class="chinese-char">勇</span></strong> (<span class="pinyin">yǒng</span>, courage) — Facing danger without hesitation</li>
        <li><strong>"Rob the rich, aid the poor"</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">劫富濟貧</span>) — Using martial power to correct social injustice</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="pullquote">
        The <span class="chinese-char">俠</span> stands apart from both the Confucian scholar-official who works within the system and the common outlaw who serves only himself. The knight-errant operates by a moral code that transcends both law and lawlessness.
      </div>
      <p>This tradition — from Sima Qian's historical records through Tang literary romance to the Song–Ming popular novel — laid the foundation for the modern wuxia genre that continues to captivate audiences worldwide.</p>
    </section>
